---
import Base from '@/layouts/Base.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
---

<Base title="About — CARB/IDE2" description="Why CARB/IDE2 exists, who builds it, and how it's licensed.">
  <div class="container-narrow py-16">
    <article class="prose-carbide">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-carbide-amber">// about</p>
    <h1>What is CARB/IDE2?</h1>
    <p>
      CARB/IDE2 is an open-source, browser-based collaborative IDE. It moves the
      whole development environment — files, terminals, chat — onto a server you
      control, so everyone working on a project sees the same thing at the same time.
    </p>

    <Callout tone="warn">
      <p><strong>“Wait, is it even an IDE?”</strong></p>
      <p>
        Honestly? Not really — yet. Most of the things that would make it a real
        IDE are still missing. But a few of them are <em>Coming Soon™</em>, and
        what exists today is a genuinely nice collaborative editing environment.
      </p>
      <p>…But the name is pretty cool.</p>
    </Callout>

    <h2>Why build another IDE?</h2>
    <p>
      Most "cloud IDEs" are hosted SaaS — convenient, but you don't own the
      infrastructure, the data, or the protocol. CARB/IDE2 is the opposite:
      self-hostable, GPLv3-licensed, and built on boring, durable tools (Ruby 4.0,
      Rails 8.1, Postgres, WebSockets). If it runs on your hardware, your data
      stays on your hardware.
    </p>

    <h2>Tech stack</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>carbide2-control</strong>: single cluster-wide Rails 8.1 app. Owns users, projects, JWT minting, and a Kubernetes operator that provisions workspace pods by watching <code>Workspace</code> Custom Resources. The only process with cluster-write RBAC.</li>
      <li><strong>carbide2-server</strong>: per-project workspace pod. Rails REST API (Puma), Postgres-backed VFS, asset serving. One deployment per project in its own namespace.</li>
      <li><strong>carbide2-worker</strong>: EventMachine WebSocket server inside each workspace pod. Owns all real-time traffic — PTY shells, bidirectional file sync via inotify, IRC-style chat, LLM agent tool calls, debug stream.</li>
      <li><strong>carbide2-client</strong>: Vue 3 + Vite SPA with Monaco editor and xterm.js. Built once; shipped into both the workspace image and the control-plane dashboard via Docker named build contexts.</li>
      <li><strong>Meta-repo (carbide2)</strong>: pins compatible versions of all four components as git submodules. Docker builds consume the client as a <code>--build-context</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>Storage</strong>: CloudNativePG (Postgres) — shared cluster, one DB per workspace. PersistentVolumeClaim per workspace. VFS lives in Postgres revision log; inotify sync keeps disk and DB in step.</li>
      <li><strong>Deploy</strong>: k3d for local dev, Kubernetes + Traefik + CNPG in production. Helm chart included.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>License</h2>
    <p>
      CARB/IDE2 is released under the <a href="https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.html">GNU GPLv3</a>.
      Run it, fork it, modify it. If you distribute changes, share them.
    </p>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <p>
      This is an early tech demo. APIs will move, features will land and leave,
      and you should not put production data in it yet. Follow the
      <a href="/blog">devblog</a> for updates.
    </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</Base>
